ce:section.ce:para:
In Fig. 4a, the average Csp2 angle for FA1, FA2, FA3, and FA4 of a4 × 4 were plotted against the folding degree. We found that plots of average Csp2 angles for FA2 and FA3 are wholly aligned with each other and they deviate from the theoretical value of 120° when folded. A similar observation was found for those of FA1 and FA4, but their plots are well distinct from those of FA2/FA3. It is interesting to note that the average Csp2 angle depends only on the folding axis but not with the size of RGQDs (see Table S1 in the Supplementary Information
                           ). Also, we noticed the different behavior of the HOMO-LUMO gap variation for FA3 to other folding axes. For FA3, the band gap increases at the advancement of the folding degree while it is reduced for other axes. This band gap widening upon folding along FA3 is also different from that observed by Zhang et al., who found that the HOMO-LUMO gap of graphene nanoribbons becomes narrower with the greater curvature [24]. This makes an interesting electronic property for curved RGQDs. The behavior of the HOMO-LUMO gap widening/narrowing upon folding is better realized in Fig. 5
                           . In Fig. 5, HOMO/LUMO energies of a3 × 3 when the structure is folded by 2 and 16°along FA2 and FA3 are displayed.
